ğŸ‘¤ HMI Account Structure

A good HMI access model includes:

1. Default (Basic) Account

View-only

Auto-login

No writing or configuration changes

Times out or locks on inactivity

2. Operator Account

Has control permissions

Limited alarm & setpoint changes

Cannot modify configuration or system files

3. Senior Operator / Manager

Can change critical setpoints

Can acknowledge/modify alarms

Should NOT have engineering privileges

4. Engineer Account

Full administrative access

Can modify HMI configuration

Should be used only when necessary

Should require MFA

This hierarchy prevents accidental or malicious misuse.

perator vs Engineer: Why Both Matter in Access Control

While engineering roles often have deep technical knowledge of PLC logic, networking, and configuration, operators hold the operational and regulatory knowledge that keeps the system safe day-to-day. A senior operator often understands:

Minimum PSI or flow required by law

Regulatory limits set by TCEQ or similar agencies

Treatment chemical minimum/maximum thresholds

Safety margins specific to that facility

How the plant behaves under load, weather, power fluctuations, or emergency conditions

Engineers may not know these operational constraints, especially if they come from outside the water sector or rotate between sites. Thatâ€™s not incompetence â€” itâ€™s just domain focus.

This is why access control should not give engineers unilateral power, and operators must still be involved in any change that could impact:

Regulatory compliance

Water quality

Minimum service pressure

Public safety

Distribution system hydraulics

Treatment process stability
